Here's the recommended approach using a custom `Window` subclass with `Preferences` for fast state persistence:

**1. Create a custom Window (`AppWindow.cs`)**

```csharp
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    private readonly NoteViewModel _viewModel;

    public AppWindow(Page page, NoteViewModel viewModel) : base(page)
    {
        _viewModel = viewModel;
    }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", _viewModel.DraftText);
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        _viewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", _viewModel.DraftText);
    }
}
```

**2. Return it from `App.xaml.cs`**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    private readonly NoteViewModel _viewModel;

    public App(NoteViewModel viewModel)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        _viewModel = viewModel;
    }

    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell(), _viewModel);
}
```

**3. Restore on first launch too** (in your page or view model)

```csharp
public NoteViewModel()
{
    // Resumed doesn't fire on first launch, so load here
    DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
}
```

### Key things to know

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| Save in **both** `OnStopped` and `OnDestroying` | Android's back button can skip `Stopped` and go straight to `Destroying` |
| `OnResumed` doesn't fire on first launch | Initial sequence is `Created â†’ Activated`, so load the draft in your constructor too |
| Keep handlers fast (<1-2s) | Slow work triggers ANR on Android or watchdog kills on iOS â€” `Preferences` is ideal for small values |
| `Deactivated â‰  Stopped` | A notification shade pull-down fires `Deactivated` but not `Stopped` â€” don't save there |
